nking about potential issues with static initializers creating connections and whether I should close those properly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Managing resources and reflection**\\n\\nI need to ensure that I close resources properly to avoid leaks, especially with the child `httpClientConnectionManager`, which may have its own resources. I’m considering whether invoking `closeConnection` will work, but it’s safer to close the client instead. I'll need to handle reflective calls carefully, especially for testing—if any `UnsupportedFeatureError` occurs, it should be caught. This means I’ll set up a try-catch around my test methods. I also want to remember to restore system properties with constants at the end.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class loading issues**\\n\\nI’m running into a potential issue with the `ClassLoader.loadClass` calls at line 466 and line 515. It seems that the active class will load the test support class using Abstract’s classloader, which could work. However, `getConstructor(emptyArray())` requires a public constructor. I wonder if public Java classes automatically have a public no-argument constructor if none is explicitly defined? Or does the default constructor end up having package-private access instead? That’s definitely something I'll need to clarify.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying constructor access**\\n\\nI’m considering whether the constructor has the same access as the class itself. According to the Java Language Specification, the default constructor does indeed have the same access, meaning it’s public. That’s good! Now, for properties, I think I need those as non-retryable and comma-separated. Also, does the child class of IOException come from java.io? And now I see that the new `DefaultHttpRequestRetryHandler` is just confirming to cast, not literally casting. I need to remember to add files next.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_lxWniykFKOFgVoOFeMppnqZe|fc